	// Since the cost is monotonic (increasing cost never hurts), we can try to satisfy the requirement greedily or with DP.
	// Due to the cyclic nature, DP is tricky because the choices are coupled across the wrap-around point (0 and n-1).

	// Since n is up to 5000, O(N^2 * K) or O(N^3) might TLE. O(N*K) or O(N log N) is safer.

	// Let's fix one element, say nums[0], and break the cycle by unrolling it to a linear array of length 2n-1,
	// and then use DP/Greedy on the linear array, handling the wrap-around separately.

	// The problem is equivalent to: select k indices, and for each selected index i,
	// ensure nums[i] > neighbor_prev AND nums[i] > neighbor_next, minimizing the sum of increases.

	// Consider the linear case first. We want to pick k indices $i_1, i_2, \dots, i_k$ and minimize cost.
	// If we select index $i$, the cost to make it a peak is $\max(0, \text{neighbor\_prev} - nums[i] + 1, \text{neighbor\_next} - nums[i] + 1)$.
